Barry:<br><br>
A person with PTSD can influence the behavior of others  transgenerationally. I did not say that those so influenced had PTSD, unless the behavior is so severe as to constitute a severe and repeated trauma itself to others. (READ my post carefully, you are jumping at things again.)<br><br>
In an analogous manner, childern raised by alcoholics may suffer behavioral or anxiety disorders as a result, but may not be alcoholics themselves. Childern who are physically tortured by alcoholic parents may be so traumatized as to manifest PTSD themselves. (I have seen this horrid stuff.)<br><br>
Among the many faces of PTSD, one expression of PTSD is a manifestation of anger in ways that can be very destructive.<br>
Actually, rage is more like it. This can be very devistating to impressionable young children.<br><br>
Clearly, this is not an &quot;exact&quot; science, and things must be considered on a case by case basis. However, my own personal experience does cause me to believe that my PTSD has affected others. I have seen it. I have done it. I acknowledge it. I am learning to control it. This is the worst part of my Vietnam War legacy, the gift that truly keeps on giving.
